description.value:
Head veil; Rectangle (incomplete) of open weave undyed linen (a), with a rolled pad (b) – the head band – sewn to the centre of one long side.

(a) The main cloth has a plain fringe at the complete end and decorative bands of thicker weft.
Warp: S-spun linen, ca 8 ends/cm
Weft: S-spun linen, ca 8 picks/cm
Edges: one fringe, two (?) selvedges, otherwise fragmentary.
Sewing threads: (a) is sewn to (b) with S-spun unbleached linen thread.

(b) curved padded roll, roughly made from undyed linen cloth, with grouped weft bands, rolled around a core of tow (linen waste) and bound with 14 sewn-on glass beads of various colours including millefiore.
Warp: S-spun linen, ca 14 threads/cm
Weft: S-spun linen, ca 13 threads/cm
Edges: torn or hidden
Sewing threads: thread binding roll in S-spun linen; thread attaching beads in S-spun Z-ply linen; running stitch

description.value: Over thirty fragments of a golden brown, woven undyed flax tunic, fabric type L. The spinning direction of the warp and weft is 's' and the weave is plain and balanced. The thread count is 12-13 warp and 9-10 weft. A button loop is present made of four 's' spun and 'z' plied threads and two 'z' spun and 's' cabled threads. The underarm gusset is set squarely rather than angled and there are side gores in the skirt. The seams are very neat, flat fell seams and the hems are turned under. Flax thread was used and consists of 2 'z' spun and 'z' plied yarns. A wooden pin pierces one of the fragments.

description.value: Woman's bag-type sprang hair-net of undyed linen with stripes of denser and less dense netting, tapering slightly at the very bottom due to the grouping of the threads in twos. A draw string was threaded through the folded bottom edge, and the ends knotted together. Along one side of the top are short loops around a narrow heading cord of purple and yellow wool, and along the opposite side are longer loops, originally threaded through with a double draw string which is now missing. Two selvedges and two looped ends remain.   The linen warp stitch gauge is c. 16 threads per cm, the threads being S-spun and Z-ply; the side seams were top-sewn with S-spun Z-ply linen thread. The heading cord consists of Z-spun purple wool and S-spun yellow wool.

description.value: Woven loin-cloth (type A) made of natural undyed wool, light tan in colour. Originally, this was a fine garment with very even spinning and weaving. The weave is plain, weft-face and the yarn is a fine thickness. The selvedge is reinforced and consists of two cords. The garment is in the form of a trapezoid with very long sides. It was shaped on a loom and not cut or hemmed. The shorter end is decorated with rows of twining and a fringe which would have hung down the front when worn. The end border has six rows of countered twining, ending on each side, in braids approximately 30mm long. The warps end in a fringe approximately 50mm long and knotted at the end. The fringe consists of two elements twisted together in a 's'-direction spiral. description.value: Undyed linen and polychrome wool textile fragment with a weft-faced tapestry weave panel at centre, surrounded by a plain weave linen ground fabric with self-bands and looped linen pile around the edges. The polychrome tapestry  weave panel depicts a fruit basket in a central medallion surrounded by compartments enclosing alternating figures of running warriors holding shields (in the four corners) and fruit baskets, all framed within the border. The vertical sides of the tapestry weave panel form long slits that are stitched to the adjacent warps in the ground fabric using an undyed, ‘s’ twist linen thread.       The warp and weft is ‘s’ twisted. The linen warp thread gauge is c. 13 per 10mm in the ground fabric. The linen weft of the ground fabric is c. 6 per 10mm. The linen weft of the tapestry panel is c. 25 per 10mm and the wool weft c. 22 per 10mm. The undyed looped linen pile consists usually of groups of 3 wefts per shed, with usually 8-10 single wefts between each group. The fringing lengths are c. 45mm. There are no finished edges.

description.value: Long cream cotton textile of plain weave, block-printed, resist-dyed and painted with a design of twelve identical female figures, facing left (as viewed), depicted in profile and in motion.  Each wears a blouse and skirt (probably not a sari) as well as necklaces, bangles and anklets: the red top and blue skirt alternates with the blue top and the red skirt.  Each figure, with the fingers of the left hand, plucks the strings of a vina, the neck of which rests on the left shoulder.  The right arm is bent, with a parrot perched on the splayed, upward-pointing fingers.  Large disc earrings or ear-plugs are depicted.  A tall, thin tree motif, with an entwining creeper, appears to the left of each figure (as viewed).  Geometric and floral bands appear at each end of the textile, running out into plain red at the end.  Geometric bands also appear at the top and bottom.  Damaged: holes, rents in top selvedge and short sides; some darning.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta model of a dramatic mask. A fragment of a model of a dramatic mask, presumably tragic, but perhaps of a Satyr. Part only of its left side remains: a prominent nose and wide eye, a fierce eyebrow and a pointed ear, an open mouth drawn down at the corner, and straight radiating hair. The eyeball is pierced, and there is a hole through the ear. This hole and its lost companion were probably used to pin or hang it on a wall. The back is plain. Pushed into one-piece mould, then Red-brown slip added on front. Red-brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

Part only of its left side remains: a prominent nose and wide eye, a fierce eyebrow and a pointed ear, an open mouth drawn down at the corner, and straight radiating hair. The eyeball is pierced, and there is a hole through the ear. This hole and its lost companion were probably used to pin or hang it on a wall. The back is plain. Pushed into one-piece mould, then Red-brown slip added on front. Red-brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta fitting (?) in form of comic mask. A model of a dramatic mask, an Old Man from the New Comedy with a short beard or, less likely, a Slave. He has a wrinkled brow, heavy eyebrows, large eyeballs and a wide open mouth. Finished along its lower edge, it is broken away elsewhere. The start of the hair survives in one place only, low down on the mask’s right side. Pressed into a one-piece mould, and the mouth cut out; the beard is striated by paring on the outside. No trace of lime wash, with paint added directly to surface of the model. Orange paint remains on the upper cheeks, below the eyes, and on the forehead, and red paint on the lips and the eyelids, both upper and lower. Green paint present on the eye ball, with black on the flat of the pupil. The beard does not appear to have been painted, left the natural brown of the fabric. Red-brown Nile silt with a grey core, abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Polychrome glazed composition tile: this expressive tile is of a captive Libyan chief. Portrayed with uplifted face and one arm bound by a rope, he wears ornamented chest-straps and a loin-cloth, the simple costume of an overlord of the ancient Libyan, or Tjehenu, tribe. His tattoos and pierced ear reflect current Libyan fashion. The surface of his body is modelled in relief, with moulded pieces like the face added separately. The tile has been reconstructed from three pieces.
